reviews.review_text: What Has Become of theBaby? I don't have my list out, but love the early stuff. To this old head any dead is great, and every show is awesome, and every show was five stars to someone. I won't dissect or critique any show, if for no other reason than i could not do it any better. The band worked hard to make us happy. Forever Grateful    Peace and Love

Raised in a lion's den On a scale of 1 to 5 this is a 50 spot.
How do I come to such a number?
Well the 1st set is like a 30
and the 2nd set is like a 20
I have been pretty much focused on 1971 / 1978 
and not to detract from those years but
THIS 1969 SOUNDBOARD!!!
So what are my favorites here
Basically everything.
With a slight tilt to MINGLEWOOD
and SILVER THREADS
Not saying those are the two best tunes here just that everything about those two tunes feeds my jones.
AND IF THE BAND HAS EVER PLAYED WITH MORE PRIMAL EMOTION THAN THIS THEN 
I HAVE PLENTY MORE GRATEFUL DEAD AHEAD!!!
Following the Velvet Underground As discussed in this nice essay about the two bands... http://deadessays.blogspot.com/2010/09/velvets-and-dead.html

A nice long night A nice long night of music. Some of these Winter-Spring shows rivaled some '72 shows in terms of length. It's nice to have an official release of this since it's a bit cleaner than the version here. As mentioned earlier, one of the earliest stops in Chicago.
Parts of this recording are very quiet  Brilliant playing.

As always, BIG THANKS to the tapers! Thanks for posting and mastering. 

IMO, this is great show. The recording is very solid as well, especially considering the year. It's not perfect, but it's a very good sounding 1969 board. The show itself is fantastic. It's no wonder they made it Dick's Picks 26. There is a wide a range of great tunes on here and the band is playing great. Bobby is low in the mix as is Pig, but Bill and especially Jerry and Phil are right up front and killing it. Right out of the gate the Dupree's is solid and the band plays well. Once they get to Cryptical>Other One>Eleven Jam>Other One, they really start to smoke. Then into It's Sin (played only 12 times) which is a real treat, a great Sittin', and later the highlight for me, the Viola>Caution Jam>Viola. Jerry plays a smoking lead at the beginning of Viola and him and Phil absolutely kill it this whole section. We also get a nice Silver Threads and Golden Needles and some other early nuggets like Doin That Rag, Hurts Me Too and Hard To Handle. But the real highlight here, IMO, is the Viola>Caution Jam>Viola...not to be missed!

There is also some great banter between Bob and Bear after Doin That Rag about turning down the drum monitors.
